There are at least two genes involved in creating  dark-colored mouse fur.
Dark fur color evolved independently on each lava flow.
Different mutations in two different genes cannot generate the same phenotype.
Under similar conditions, natural selection can favor similar adaptations.

This is a gland within the mesentery between the stomach and small intestine; it produces insulin and glucagon and secretes the hormones into the bloodstream. It also secretes digestive enzymes into the small intestine.
A thin piece of skeletal muscle that separates the thoracic and abdominal cavities; integral to the process of respiration.
Either of the pair of excretory organs within which metabolic wastes are removed and water and certain ions are resorbed from the blood; forms urine.
One of a pair of tubes connecting the kidneys to the urinary bladder.
One of the pair of male sex organs that produces sperm; forms within the abdomen and later descends into the scrotum.
One of a pair of coiled tubes that carry ova (eggs) from the ovary to the uterine horn.
The protective membrane that surrounds the heart; contains pericardial fluid that lubricates and cushions the heart.

A gland located on the ventral surface of the cervical region of the pig, lateral to the trachea (also has a thoracic portion located on the anterior ventral side of the heart). This gland is critical to immune function as it is responsible for the development and maturation of T cells. After a mammal reaches sexual maturity, the gland shrinks to a much smaller size.

One of two lower chambers of the heart; the left forces blood into the aorta, and the right forces blood into the pulmonary arteries. Because it pumps blood throughout the body, the left is typically larger than the right, which pumps blood solely to the lungs.

Either of the two upper chambers of the heart. The left receives oxygenated blood into the heart via the pulmonary veins, and the right receives deoxygenated blood from the superior and inferior venae cavae.
Located between the pharynx and the trachea, commonly called the “voice box” because it contains the vocal cords.

An endocrine gland located on the ventral surface of the trachea that secretes hormones that act on every cell in the body. This gland’s hormones control metabolism, growth rate, and calcium levels in the organism. The hormones also are required for the development of the skeleton, muscles, and sex organs.
Cartilage-lined airway located between the larynx and the bronchi; commonly called “the windpipe.”
The principal organ of the respiratory system, responsible for gas exchange.
Muscular tube that connects the pharynx to the stomach.
Folds in the stomach that allow it to expand. They also contain the gastric glands for digestion.
